entry.title: Fix Mandatory Re-auth MacOS and iOS Strings
entry.content:
This CL fixes the strings on MacOS for mandatory re-auth. The MacOS

operating system appends periods to the end of the string in addition to

prepending "Google Chrome is trying to" before the string. The

prepending was handled correctly, but due to the fact that there was a

period already in the string, we ended up having two periods.



Here is an example of a prompt with two periods:

https://screenshot.googleplex.com/AjMJGEpnmMTECeV



This CL removes the periods at the end for MacOS, and also moves all of

the strings into the common components/autofill_payments_strings.grdp

file. This is okay because we do not need to differentiate between

Chromium and Google Chrome for these strings on MacOS, that is

automatically handled.



This CL also updates the iOS string to say "Chrome" instead of "Google

Chrome", and the corresponding translation screenshot.

entry.title: Revert "[ios/uno] Stop migrating most global SelectedTypes prefs"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 1c8eda03211c693548e5e4f32d60ad09c504c5df.



Reason for revert: Landed accidentally



Original change's description:

> [ios/uno] Stop migrating most global SelectedTypes prefs

>

> Behavior changes are behind the existing

> kReplaceSyncPromosWithSignInPromos flag.

> Before this CL, the current value of the global prefs was taken into

> account for the new per-account prefs introduced by UNO. The motivation

> was that sync happens to honor the global prefs even for signed-in

> non-syncing users today. "So we'd better not start syncing types

> that were previously disabled".

>

> Well, this behavior is in fact a bug [1]. Pre-UNO, signed-in

> non-syncing users cannot configure most such prefs via any UI.

> Meaning some data types could be disabled without any apparent reason.

> We can even achieve this broken state by:

> - Enabling sync.

> - Disabling some types.

> - Disabling sync (keeps data type prefs).

> - Signing in without syncing.

>

> In this CL the migration logic stops reading the global prefs for most

> types, i.e. leaves the new account-scoped prefs in their default

> states. There is one exception: passwords, which *does* currently

> expose a toggle reading/writing the global pref. So that one needs

> to stay. We also use the occasion to fix a tangentially related bug:

> only the user-configurable pref should be read, not the one from

> enterprise policies.

>

> The main point of this CL is making it easier (in follow-ups) to

> use the account-scoped prefs also on other platforms.

>

> [1] Honoring the managed version of the pref is still important to

> respect the SyncTypesListDisabled policy. That's still guaranteed by

> IsTypeManagedByPolicy().

entry.title: Revert "Use the built-in Cronet telemetry stack"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 3edea021bad8fdafebc2d11fb9bdc0266ce6d0e3.



Reason for revert: Needed for another revert: https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5041483



Bug: https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1503204



Original change's description:

> Use the built-in Cronet telemetry stack

>

> Before this CL, Cronet expected to be shipped with a CronetLoggerImpl

> class that lives outside of Chromium:

>

> - In the case of AOSP Cronet, that class would be built from AOSP along

> with the rest of Cronet;

> - In the case of Cronet embedded in Google 1P apps and Google Play

> Services it would be built from an internal Google repo and the

> resulting compiled class would be injected into the Cronet JAR at APK

> build time;

> - In any other cases (e.g. Maven) the class would not be present at

> all.

>

> The above setup is extremely contrived and requires maintaining an

> API/ABI boundary across 3 different repos, making this code very painful

> to maintain. We have to juggle between all these repos every time we

> make any changes to telemetry atom schemas, which is something we expect

> to do somewhat regularly in the future. This is not sustainable.

>

> This CL simplifies the whole setup by making Cronet use the telemetry

> code that was recently imported from AOSP into Chromium for this

> purpose. From this point on, the entire telemetry logic lives in

> Chromium and can be maintained just like the rest of Cronet code in the

> normal way.

>

> The AOSP and internal code that attempts to inject a CronetLoggerImpl

> class will have no effect after this CL - that code will become dead and

> we should clean it up as soon as this commit makes it to these repos.

>

> The only downside of this change is that the atom definition still lives

> elsewhere - the source of truth for that is in an internal Google

> repo since the code that consumes the telemetry data is Google-internal.

> The CronetStatsLog code is supposed to be autogenerated at build time

> from the atom definition, but the relevant code generator only exists in

> AOSP (under the name "stats-log-api-gen") and in the internal repo - it

> does not exist in Chromium. So, for now, we'll have to run the code

> generator manually and then manually copy its output over to Chromium,

> every time we change atom definitions. This is not ideal, but that's a

> small price to pay for the massive simplification that this CL brings.

> Eventually we should solve this by having the atom proto definition in

> Chromium (ideally autosynced from the internal repo) and then

> autogenerate the logging code from it at build time in Chromium.

>

AndroidMetricsServiceClient was listening to. Given that this class is a

could theoretically also be cases where the RenderWidgetHostImpl would

send the event that don't make it through now because a WebContents

doesn't exist; but I believe these should be fairly rare for the types

of events that we are actually listening to here.

entry.title: [ios/uno] Stop migrating most global SelectedTypes prefs
entry.content:
Behavior changes are behind the existing

kReplaceSyncPromosWithSignInPromos flag.

Before this CL, the current value of the global prefs was taken into

account for the new per-account prefs introduced by UNO. The motivation

was that sync happens to honor the global prefs even for signed-in

non-syncing users today. "So we'd better not start syncing types

that were previously disabled".



Well, this behavior is in fact a bug [1]. Pre-UNO, signed-in

non-syncing users cannot configure most such prefs via any UI.

Meaning some data types could be disabled without any apparent reason.

We can even achieve this broken state by:

- Enabling sync.

- Disabling some types.

- Disabling sync (keeps data type prefs).

- Signing in without syncing.



In this CL the migration logic stops reading the global prefs for most

types, i.e. leaves the new account-scoped prefs in their default

states. There is one exception: passwords, which *does* currently

expose a toggle reading/writing the global pref. So that one needs

to stay. We also use the occasion to fix a tangentially related bug:

only the user-configurable pref should be read, not the one from

enterprise policies.



The main point of this CL is making it easier (in follow-ups) to

use the account-scoped prefs also on other platforms.



[1] Honoring the managed version of the pref is still important to

respect the SyncTypesListDisabled policy. That's still guaranteed by

IsTypeManagedByPolicy().

entry.title: [mullet m2] Store profile id in field-by-field filling suggestions.
entry.content:
We want to add two new types of field-by-field filling:

1. Full name

2. Street name



However, differently from the current usages where the text rendered in

the suggestion is what is entered the field (Suggestion::main_text),

these two new suggestions will have different main text values, they

will work as follows:



- If the trigger field is not of name group a "Fill full name"

suggestion is added, it will be of PopupItemId::kFieldByFieldFilling

type and fill the FULL_NAME.

- If the trigger field is not of address group a "Fill address"

suggestion is added, it will also be field-by-field filling and it

will fill the STREET_ADDRESS information (if it exists, naturally).



This change is a noop and makes it possible for the two suggestions

above to be introduced in a follow up.



I will also start using this value in the follow up CL.

Reason for revert: This CL looks related to https://crbug.com/1503141



Original change's description:

> Reland "Use fastset for VRR modesetting"

>

> This is a reland of commit 216d3120eaa516acf457a213b3e3d7df334cb33d

>

> This change differs from the original by refactoring memory management

> of the snapshots used by DisplayConfiguratorTest. The updated code

> ensures that the cache will not contain references to freed snapshots,

> which was previously the cause of msan failures which reverted the

> original change.

>

> Original change's description:

> > Use fastset for VRR modesetting

> >

> > This change enforces the use of seamless modesetting for changes

> > affecting the VRR_ENABLED crtc property, which has previously always

> > allowed full modesets. Now that support for VRR fastsetting has been

> > backported, it is not necessary to allow full modesets when changing

> > the VRR_ENABLED state.

> >

> > This change also removes a workaround which required full modesetting

> > to change the refresh rate throttling state whenever VRR_ENABLED was

> > active. Now that the fix has been backported, seamless modesets can be
